Analyzed the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs-Boson has excited some insight last summer, and this is for good reason.
In fact, one believes that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence of the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - has been predicted, but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists it is not completely sure that it really is Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is strongly similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Furthermore, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely secure about it.
Let’s still assume that it’s actually Higgs, because it seems that there’s only a small risk of deceit, and let’s look at what it’s going on.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects to not be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strong as you will hurt yourself.
For even if the particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", with this "state" consisting generally of some of their properties.
From this, the physicists share the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing): the mesons we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic power.
Indeed, if a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" precisely in this place, about like a rod that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "bearers of force".
Stabler field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order to show that boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energy, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be scattered by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, they are not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others don’t - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep on the refrigerator itself.
And equally not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it possess a mass, while the others (like the photon) do not possess a mass.
What can all these research be "good" for now, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine all differences between observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who hope most likely that such deviations will be found, since the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great defects, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of these researches on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell laboratories did not suspect their works would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and the laser in 1962 himself developed the first permanent string laser (the first were pulsed) - already told us that the laser was considered in the beginning rather than a "lab playing".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics in 1969.
Although it wasn’t the original purpose, this sensor today serves as “eye” to all digital cameras worldwide and gave him the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it...
