The disease does her work: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he agrees to resign to help with dinner.
Bravely, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring his medications to him, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest desire is to heal my diarrhea because this is humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for this evil.
“In the course of our life we learn that a man standing is pinching,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the home of Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the ability of the person" to take a step back, he notes.
Because, according to several people working in palliative care, great events take place in the middle of these backstages.
Patients entered into the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer accumulated by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called “healing” care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
