“I have good children,” she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she says before she accepts to put her on a mask that helps her breathing.
In the next few days, she still expects a last visit to her son, who comes from Italy.
At home Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers offers personal care and assistance in food intake.
Palliative care is then used when there are no other options.
To make the death more pleasant.
In Quebec, 11,700 inhabitants come a bed for palliative care.
This is very little when you take into account that one day we will all die.
Life is continued here under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Mouth care is given to the dying person with Brandy or Pepsi, depending on the desire.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died throughout the night.
This morning his son will drunk the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help families and patients equally," reports the nursing director Nathalie Savard.
At home Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his head pillows while attacking to his honor, a 36-year-old young man who is surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children dies in a tragic way after he tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds are always involved with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Christiane Martel.
53% of Victor-Gadbois’ home-inserted patients come from their residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to a care that is intended to alleviate patients’ suffering when they have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in a hospital or in a nursing house.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the company for domestic palliative care in the largest Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Exactly this great insufficiency in Quebec’s health care ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care are confronting the adoption of a death aid and assisted suicide law with concerns.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their contradiction to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to move to the death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days with great pain in the emergency hospital without taking measures to relief her.
I’m afraid that patients want to die only because they don’t get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst predictions to the last day.
Hélène Richard’s survival chances were already minimal when she discontinued complicating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I'm going to discontinue treatment, she answered me that she regretted that I was up for the fight, she told.
But she told me that I'm at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for failing to accept this desire after their pain has been allevied by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly said that palliative care in pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Montreal Household Palliative Care Society, 8% of the patients do not address pain treatment.
At the end of life, physicians are therefore often resorting to the terminal sedation, which is based on either sporadic or permanent blowing the patient until the time of his death.
We cannot do any longer as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be increasingly able to use this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved, all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to inject me,” but “I want my pain to be alleviated.”
