Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits" that are used to move forward in a video game that you can win or buy by gambling (and sometimes re-exchange).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed every time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in reality between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are available throughout the public account account book spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is launched on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, possessing the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a partition of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole "hacks".
The aim is to find the number that results in a special fingerprint (many zero at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the right.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay two times very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains without linking, as both of them have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task will receive 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent an inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred millionth, leaving a certain space.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with every improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
