Other articles on spacecraft appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of spacecraft are dedicated.
The article of Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space society.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was not expected that space exploration would have the future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA endeavored to join the International Federation for Spacecraft, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became an ordinary member already in autumn 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been largely involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was approximately 80 cm long and did not weigh entirely 5 kg.
Later, an enhanced version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, the Błędow Desert began flight tests with the RM-2 two-stage missile.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to perform real scientific work - the RM-34 missile should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring height winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was stopped.
Followers of the first RM-type missiles were the Meteor-1 missile developed in 1962 to 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the start weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed by this missile, which differ from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with 0.4 liters of capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight height of all three types was 37 km.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a start weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a load of 10 kg at a height of approximately 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth noting the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which two years later followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites in the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
