The conclusion of the Summit of Unasur without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Declaration of Lima, which was announced previously and theoretically should be signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of the Unasur, but sources in the State and Presidential Chancellor initially informed that they would pass it after the Clausur, but subsequently declared that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian Government.
For questions about the text, they stated that the content was depicted by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in short statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information on the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists was received by the press spokesmans of some of the governments present at the meeting of Unasur, but not from Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was disseminated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which created discomfort among the hundreds of journalists of various national and international media that demanded more information.
Then the President’s Office of Peru sent the media an email with the “Declaration of conclusion” of the summit, but it was Humala’s Declaration and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru was host of the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even at this occasion, despite the urgent call by the press, the so-called declaration of Lima, which was previously announced, was not published.
On the official website of ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities emphasized that information systems would be available for journalists, but they highly restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the common commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment by the Court of Justice of Den Haag, which involved a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins on Monday in Den Haag, in the process of inducing Lima against Santiago to listen to the calls of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we present to this International Court," Humala and his Chilean counter said.
“Chile was, is and remains a country that comply with international laws, seeks peaceful dispute solutions, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts,” Piñera adds and greeted Humala with a hand pressure before the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both Presidents that they would be subject to the IGH was made after Colombia, after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which felt it was a serious mistake, had filed a lawsuit against the Bogota Agreement, in which it was agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner, were present.
Paraguay, who has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after his President Fernando Lugo was dismissed, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit in Lima shortly after midnight.
The head of state left the final document, which reported that 16 decisions were made and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries on a total investment amount of $17 billion.
