With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) cannot take triumphful traits, but is intended to expand our production performance and show our people a better future,” Humala added.
“We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects to improve the spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open new economic forms,” the Peruvian president said in a read statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, living on the queraches of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which should ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighborhood relations was another aspect emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, before he began attending the regional meeting, said he expected a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to respect the maritime conflict after a judgment of the IGH questioned by Bogotá.
